The RRS Charles Darwin Cruise 105 took place in the Galician CTZ
from 29 May to 20 June 1997 as part of the OMEX II-II sampling
strategy. The cruise was divided into two legs: leg A ran from 29
May to 8 June while leg B ran from 10 to 20 June. The main
objectives of the cruise were:

\begin{itemize}
  \item  make a detailed swath bathymetry of the slope topography of the
  region during leg A.(XBT WERE DEPLOYED, CHECK)
  \item  to deploy a
bottom-mounted acoustic Doppler current profiler at 156m depth and
a mooring of four current meter in 686m, both near 42\deg 40'N,
  \item to sample a grid of CTD stations typically 10km apart on
  cross slope sections ranging from 43\deg N to 41\deg 25' every 10' and
  covering depths from 100m on the shelf to 3000m offshore,
  including the OMEX reference stations,
  \item to record underway ADCP, temperature, salinity,
  fluorescence, transmittance and irradiance.
\end{itemize}
The sampling of the slope bottom topography was carried out during
leg A and only underway Temperature, Salinity and irradiance were
recorded for that period. The CTD grid sampling took place during
leg B. The grid stations were roughly separated 10 by 18 km,
smaller than the local internal Rossby radius (give number from
Haynes thesis) which provided enough detail to resolve mesoscale
structures. However, the 10 days it took to complete the survey
reduced the efficiency to identify synoptic mesoscale signals.
Besides the standard CTD measurements of Temperature, Salinity and
Pressure, the instrument was equipped with sensors for recording
fluorescence, dissolved oxygen, radiance, transmittance and
optical backscatter. Other biological data were measured from
water samples from many of the stations (i.e. nutrients, primary
production, pigments, DOC, bacteria, POC, SPM among others) and
plankton samples were obtained from night and day net hauls and
LHPR tows. Downwelling favourable wind conditions were typical for
the first 4 days of the cruise with increasing northerly winds
thereafter until the end of the cruise on 20 June. The moorings
were deployed on the first day (10 June) and the CTD grid started
on the following day due to problems with the CTD bottle firing.
Nonetheless, CTD transects were only disrupted to perform LHPR
tows and on 14 June to inspect the deep-tow cable. The 3
northernmost lines (Transects N,O and P,
Fig~\ref{fig:cd105stations} had already been done but the need to
test the cable in deep water meant the vessel steamed southward
towards the southern most deep station and proceeded the grid
northwards.
