The typical water mass distribution explained in
Chapter~\ref{ch:litrev} was well represented in CD105 cruise. The
upper layer of the Iberian coastal ocean was divided into a
surface layer which included the surface mixed layer and the
seasonal thermocline down to 100m, and a sub-surface layer, where
the permanent thermocline lied, down to 400m, where the influence
of the mediterranean outflow began. The sub-surface layer had the
characteristic linear relationship between temperature and
salinity typical of eastern North Atlantic Central Waters (NACW).

From the CTDs collected during the cruise 6 sub-regions have been
defined to investigate the T-S differences among them
(Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ts}). Also included in the graph are the
subdivisions to the NACW as \enawt and \enawp, and their shared
limit H defined by \cite{rios92}. The 6 sub-regions correspond to
latitudinal and zonal variations in relation to the poleward flow
and the regions of influence of the ``Rias Bajas'' and the
``Minho'' river. Their influence can be seen in the top 10-25m for
the regions called Southward Coastal Jet (SCJ) and Minho runoff
(M) (see Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ts}b for their exact location). Their
surface salinity fell below 35 psu at the stations nearer to
shore, and increased offshore.

The bulk of the central waters are \enawt, with only a small
portion laying over the \enawp line definition. As we move
northward (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ts}c), the surface salinity decreases
defining a high salinity maximum at the level of the \enawt (100m)
which gradually reduces with latitude. The exemption is the
southward coastal jet region, where the maximum is of similar
value to the North nearshore region suggesting the southward
advection of waters from the poleward flow.

Below the central waters we find the Mediterranean Water (MW) high
salinity core, which correspond to the vein of MW flowing
northwards along the continental slope between 400-500m identified
by \citeN{ambar83}. No evidences were found of the two main
outflow cores of MW normally located offshore at $\approx$750 and
$\approx$1250m \cite{zenk90}. The MW high salinity core reduced
with latitude in agreement with its northward advection.
\subsection{Horizontal Fields}
\subsubsection{Near-Surface (5m) fields}
The near-surface salinity distribution (5m) recorded from the
thermosaligraph for leg A and B are shown in
Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}. Although it is difficult to consider them
as true synoptic fields in the light of the wind changes occurred
during the cruise they will be discuss as snapshots. The
temperature fields are not discussed here as they showed a strong
diurnal heating that masked any of the spatial structures. The
salinity in this region can be used as a circulation tracer
because the T-S characteristics in the upper layer (top 100m) are
roughly perpendicular to the isopycnals (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ts}a).

During leg A (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}a) the salinity range was
small in most of the area (36.08-35.70psu) with the exception of
an isolated low salinity region marked as ``L'' in the graph where
it reached values of 35.4psu. Salinity generally decreased with
latitude, and associated meridional differences were larger than
zonal ones. The region of highest salinity ($>36psu$) in the SW
corner of the graph correspond to an area of high temperatures in
Fig~\ref{fig:cd105sst}a and the warm tongue extending from it has
a rough equivalent in the salinity field, both turning inshore at
$\sim$42.4\deg N. Near the location of E2
(Fig~\ref{fig:cd105sst}a) in Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}a, a local
salinity maxima exists. The low salinity region ``L'' is part of a
relatively low salinity tongue which seems to have its origin in
the ``Rias Bajas'' (Fig~\ref{fig:largebathy}), the coastal
indentations between 42.2\deg and 42.5\deg N. The tongue turns
southwards at -9.5\deg W, rather than northwards as it would have
been expected from freshwater plume dynamics. Note that along that
longitude a colder water band can be seen in
Fig~\ref{fig:cd105sst}a parallel to the offshore warm tongue. The
SST composite image of leg A has a similar signature in the near
surface salinity field, with warmer temperatures related to higher
salinities. The salty offshore water tongue turns inshore north of
42.5\deg N.

In leg B, the sampling included coastal stations at depths $<100m$
and the salinity range increased to include lower values (36-30.5
psu). The period was characterized by weak upwelling favourable
winds except for the time of the three northernmost sections. The
shoreward limit covered during leg A shows lower salinities in leg
B (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}b), which further decrease onshore,
particularly south of 42.75\deg N. This lead to the formation of a
strong salinity front which was enhanced south of 42.25\deg N due
to the presence of the high salinity tongue offshore (P in the
graph) with $\nabla S>0.4psu$. The high salinity tongue P
broadened during leg B and split at 42.25\deg N, one branch
turning offshore at that latitude, while the other progressed
northwards only to turn offshore further north. The high salinity
structure E is now better defined with values $>38.85$ psu.
Salinity further decreased in the low salinity tongue (L in leg
A), and extended offshore to -10\deg W south of E.
