\subsubsection{Near-Surface (15m) fields} Horizontal fields at the
level of the shallowest reliable ADCP bin (12m bin centred at 15m
depth) are shown in Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_15m}. The salinity and
fluorescence contours (\ref{fig:cd105_15m}a-b) show some
fundamental differences when compare to the 5m fields. The
freshwater coastal band south of 42.15\deg~N has now disappeared
from the salinity plot although it is still visible in the
fluorescence field as a high fluorescence narrow band 15km off the
coast. The salty tongue P now shows two branches, the offshore
branch which was already present in Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}a and b,
and a coastal branch running along the slope until 42.15\deg~N
which was also visible in Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}a. The low
salinity region L is still extending offshore but minimum values
($<35.5$) are now closer to shore than in Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ths}b.
The eddy E is still visible and relatively high salinities are
found flowing onshore similar to the salinity field of leg A
(north of 42.7\deg N), and offshore like in leg B. The
fluorescence field shows a similar pattern to the 5m contour,
however higher values extend further offshore. Part of the high
fluorescence plume turns southwards at 9.75\deg W 42\deg N, while
a smaller tongue turns northward offshore the high salinity eddy
E. The poleward branching is also noticeable in the fluorescence
data south of 42\deg N.

ADCP current vectors (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_15m}c) were averaged in
cells of 0.05x0.05\deg for clarity. The highest velocities
($>$25\velc) were associated with a contorted poleward flow, but
some areas showed small velocities ($\thicksim$ 5\velc) which were
contaminated by tidal flows of similar order predicted for the
region \cite{fanjul97}. Nonetheless, the raw ADCP data agrees with
the salinity and fluorescence fields. The two branches of the
poleward flow in the southern region shows northward vectors of
15-20\velc for the coastal branch and $>25$\velc for the offshore
one. In the northern limit the two poleward branches were also
measured by the ADCP with stronger flow at the coastal branch
($\thicksim$ 30\velc) than at the offshore one ($\thicksim$
15\velc). Anticyclonic circulation was associated with the high
salinity eddy E and offshore flow was measured at 42.25\deg N
associated with the offshore extending low salinity tongue L. The
southward extension of the high fluorescence plume can also be
seen in the current vectors with velocities of $\thicksim$
15\velc. A strong southward coastal current ($\thicksim$ 25\velc)
was measured between 42.5\deg-42\deg N.

In order to get rid of the current fluctuations due to tidal and
inertial currents the non-divergent part of the flow was
calculated (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_15m}d). Overlaid on the current
vectors are contours of streamfunction transport. It shows a broad
contorted poleward flow. Much of its transport enters the region
west of 10\deg W with only 30\% (0.02Sv) coming from the south and
forming the coastal branch. The latter joins the southward coastal
current veering offshore (0.03Sv) and merges with the offshore
branch. Most of it leaves the region between 42\deg-42.5\deg N
(0.08Sv) but 0.03Sv proceeds northwards with lower salinity after
having mixed with the low salinity coastal current. The flow
further splits into the offshore (0.01Sv) and the coastal poleward
current (0.02Sv).
