\subsubsection{Sub-surface (50m) fields}
The mixed layer distribution (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105ml}) was
calculated using $\Delta \sigma_{t}=0.1$\dens and represents a
measure of the layer that has been recently mixed
\cite{brainerd95}. Maximum depths ($>40m$) were measured in the
northern limit in association with the poleward flow while minimum
values were encountered near-coast south of 42.25\deg N. The
latter corresponds to the region influenced by the freshwater
runoff from the Mi\~{n}o river. The low salinity plume L had
typical mixed layer depths of 20m. The centre of the eddy E was
characterized by deeper mixed layer depths than surrounding waters
by as much as 20m.

The salinity field below the mixed layer ( at 50m,
Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_51m}a) shows an intensified offshore poleward
flow extending along the western limit of the grid at all sampled
latitudes. Its salinity signal  is more clearly defined than at
shallower levels, with peak salinities above 36 psu, higher than
the coastal branch (35.95-35.90 psu). The latter is starting to
detach from the offshore branch and both are separated by a
meridional band of relatively lower salinity ($<35.90 psu$). The
signal of the offshore high salinity eddy E, is still visible but
appears shifted to the west. No sign of the coastal freshwater
plume from shallower levels is apparent at 50m. Low salinities
($<35.9 psu$) are mainly found north of 42.5\deg N at the coast,
and offshore progressively northwards.

The fluorescence field (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_51m}b) also lacks the
presence of coastal freshwater runoffs seen in
Fig~\ref{fig:cd105chl5m}-\ref{fig:cd105ths}. Instead the field
corresponds to a patchy distribution of high fluorescence centres
(0.5-0.65V) which seem to be related to the poleward flow and the
eddy E seen in the salinity, although they were not present at
shallower levels.

