\subsubsection{Sub-surface (100m) fields}
The distribution of properties at 100m (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_100m})
shows again the offshore salty and warm poleward flow, now fully
detached from its coastal branch (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_100m}a-b) by
a low salinity-temperature band running parallel to the coast. On
the coast, two regions north and south of the Rias Bajas had
waters with similar thermohaline properties to waters within the
poleward flow and constituted the remains of the coastal poleward
flow. The eddy E is still visible with 0.05 (0.2\deg) salinity
(temperature) anomalies although its centre is again shifted
northwest with respect to the flow field
(Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_100m}c-d).

The raw flow field (Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_100m}c) is now less
energetic than at previous depths. The offshore poleward flow
reached peak velocities of 15\velc immediately southwest of the
eddy E, and at its northern coastal branch, and were of comparable
value to the equatorward current associated with the low salinity
and temperature band. The non-divergent current field
(Fig~\ref{fig:cd105_100m}d) shows clearly the basic flow field of
the offshore poleward flow, the anticyclonic eddy, the northern
coastal poleward current and the equatorward flow. The cyclonic
circulation associated with the southern coastal poleward flow was
still visible if weakened and so did the offshore flow at
42.25\deg N.

