What I think we're looking at here:

First the poleward flow occupies the shelfbreak, normally
extending to the surface and in most cases nearly the whole of the
shelf. Flow could be northward everywhere, specially since river
runoff would also turn northwards due to coriolis. At some point,
extreme upwelling forces the poleward current to move offshore.
This would mean lifting of isopycnals and erosion of the
shelf-break poleward flow. Here we haven't got evidences of
upwelling, but the poleward flow is moved offshore. It reaches its
maximum westward position opposite the Rias Bajas, and offshore
flow is measured there. It is tempting to think that the
funnelling effect of the Rias in the wind can cause offshore wind
driven currents, if not upwelling along the whole coast. Other
possibility is the release of piled up water in the Rias when
northward winds weaken. As the poleward flow moves offshore, it
leaves space for an equatorward geostrophic flow to develop in
response to the sloping isopycnals of the shoreward side of the
poleward. Also, at some of the transects, particularly those in
the middle of the grid, show a double relatively high salinity
core at depths below 150-200m, which could represent the previous
and present position of the poleward flow, that take longer to
erode?.

The offshore extension of the low salinity plume has values not
less than 35.5, when we could have expected lower values like
further south off the mi\~{n}o mouth. Could be that waters from
the Rias get piled up inside the Rias, mixed with shelf waters,
and when southerly winds relax or change to northerly winds the
waters are flushed to the shelf.

Coastal branch gets switch on and off depending on wind forcing?,
while offshore branch is more permanent feature in winter, or once
it's been advected offshore?. Maybe the V transect shows the
shifting from the coastal branch that was active during the last
storm, to the offshore location due to the change in winds.
